                    <center>   <img src="{% static "img/hydrogen_series0.png" %}" width="500"></center><br><br>
                    Each element in nature have a characteristic spectral emmision decomposition, which is used as a ``fingerprint'' that allow us to determine the chemical content of many substances. This is for example, how we deduce the elemtary content of starts, galaxies, cosmic dust, etc.<br><br> 
Let's return to the characteristic potential energy for the Hydrogen atom,
                    \begin{equation}
                    U(r)=-{1\over 4\pi\epsilon_0}{e^2\over r}\,.
                    \end{equation}
                    We see that it only depends on the radius (a potential that only depends on the radius, is called a <b>central potential</b>), and henceforth, it would be unconvenient to use cartesian coordinates, and we need to rewrite Schrodinger equation in the more convenient Spherical coordinates,<br><br>
		    <h2>Quick Review of Spherical Coordinates</h2>
		    Do you remember the coordinate transformation from spherical coordinates to Cartesian coordinates? 

                    <center>   <img src="{% static "img/spherical0.png" %}" width="500"></center><br><br>
			<ol  style="line-height:300%" type="A">
		 <br>   <img src="{% static "img/iclicker.png" %}" width="100"> <br>
		     <!-- longer -->
		 <li> $x = r\,\cos\theta\cos\phi\,\quad y = r\,\sin\theta\sin\phi\,\quad  y = r\,\cos\phi$</li>
		 <li> $x = r\,\sin\theta\cos\phi\,\quad y = r\,\sin\theta\sin\phi\,\quad  y = r\,\cos\phi$</li>
	 	 <li> $x = r\,\sin\theta\cos\phi\,\quad y = r\,\sin\theta\sin\phi\,\quad  y = r\,\sin\phi$</li>
		 <li> I do not remember </li>
				</ol>
	<br><br>


